The flight logbook has been officially activated. I have 2.3 hours of flying records ^_^
#TeaganAir
If I were to describe what it's like to fly a small aircraft, I would say it's like riding a motorcycle/motorized all-terrain vehicle and a boat combined at 4000 feet above ground.
On the ground, things can change quickly. The ground is somewhat unstable, so you need a motorcycle/motorized all-terrain vehicle.
Additionally, you might not know that when driving a plane on the ground, it's controlled with your feet, not the joystick. It uses rudder pedals and brakes. It's not like a car.
When flying in the air, you will feel the turbulence and shaking, similar to being on a boat on water. Although you can control the plane, sometimes the air currents will make you a bit dizzy, so you need to adapt to flying in the air, just like sailors adapt to sailing.
There is also a random fun fact about this:
Flying is very tiring. Today my back and legs hurt badly, feeling as if I had worked out at the gym.
This is not as simple as taking a drive around on Sunday. To me, a beginner, it feels more like a sport than a cruise.
Dear friends, Happy Saturday. Welcome to 4,000 feet in the air.
Tomorrow I will fly again, and we will practice stall and slow flight.
The weather today was not very stable but super interesting. We practiced slow flight and stalls. Our ground speed dropped to 16 miles per hour, while our airspeed was still 65 miles per hour.
The weather was clear today, although it was a bit foggy up high, the view was still fantastic.
